      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Combine soy sauce, water, brown sugar, rice vinegar, sesame oil, ginger, garlic, and honey in a medium bowl. Whisk everything together and set it aside.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Place chicken breasts in the slow cooker and pour sauce on top. Cook on low for 3½ to 4 hours.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Remove chicken from slow cooker and shred, set aside.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Place liquid from the slow cooker and water into a saucepan. Then bring to a boil over medium-high heat. While stirring the liquid, add cornstarch a little at a time and stir until thickened. Let boil for 1 minute and stir occasionally.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Pour sauce over shredded chicken and stir to combine.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Serve over rice and garnish with green onions and sesame seeds.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Storage",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "In the fridge - If you have any leftover teriyaki chicken, you can store it in the fridge for up to 3 days. Once it has completely cooled, transfer it into a sealed, air-tight container before placing it into the fridge. When you are ready to reheat it, individual portions can be heated in the microwave for 1.5 minutes or until warm. Larger portions can be heated in the oven. Put the chicken in a pan and cover it with foil so that it won’t dry out. Then bake it at 350 degrees for 15 minutes.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "In the freezer - You can also freeze this slow cooker teriyaki chicken. You can divide it into small portions or freeze it all together, just make sure that it is in a sealed, freezer-safe container. It will last for up to 8 weeks. When you are ready to enjoy, thaw it completely in the fridge, then reheat as directed above",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": "A few of the more common issues, and what tends to fix them.",
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Switch to low and shorter, or pick a fattier cut (shoulder, shin, chuck). Eight hours on low is the safe sweet spot for most cuts.",
              "cause": "Cooked on high too long, or the cut was too lean.",
              "symptom": "Meat is stringy or dry"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Lift the lid for the last 30 minutes on high, or transfer the sauce to a saucepan and reduce on the hob.",
              "cause": "Slow cookers don't evaporate, every drop of liquid stays in.",
              "symptom": "Sauce is watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add anything that cooks in under 20 minutes in the last half-hour. Root veg can go in from the beginning.",
              "cause": "Soft veg (courgette, peas, leafy greens) added at the start.",
              "symptom": "Vegetables are mush"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Brown meat in a pan first, five minutes a side. The fond at the bottom of the pan goes in too. Worth the extra washing-up.",
              "cause": "Meat went in raw without browning.",
              "symptom": "Lacks depth"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "If something goes wrong"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Variations",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Hob version: brown the meat, then transfer to a casserole dish in a 150°C oven for the same length of time, 3 to 4 hours.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Vegetarian: replace meat with 600 g mixed root veg and 200 g lentils; cut cooking time by a third.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make ahead, freezing, leftovers",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The slow cooker is the make-ahead.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Japanese home cooking trusts the ingredient. Dashi, soy, mirin, sake, used in restraint, never to dominate. The dish belongs to that quiet tradition.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
